  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      Malnutrition is very common in critically ill patients. It is quite important to evaluate
      nutritional status precisely. Heyland et al firstly reported NUTRIC score including age,
      APACHE II score, SOFA score, number of commorbidities, days from hospital to ICU admission
      and IL-6. Because the IL-6 is not routinely checked at ICU. A modified NUTRIC score without
      IL-6 is more practical. Previous studies showed lower in-hospital mortality in higher
      nutritional risk patients with higher caloric intake compared with lower caloric intake.
      However, there is still controversial regarding the in-hospital mortality between full
      caloric feeding and permissive underfeeding in critically ill patients. Herein the
      investigators conduct a study to investigate what kinds of nutritional supplements will
      decrease in-hospital mortality in different nutritional risk patients.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
